{
  "texts": [
    "In their defense, the Home Office claimed that legal categories fail to grasp most real-life cases where automated systems segment decisionmaking but do not replace humans entirely.",
    "Existing legal scholarship has focused on the limited protective function of the GDPR in relation to ADM, contending that Article 22 GDPR is too narrow in scope, 6 needs further authoritative interpretation, 7 does not provide rights and protection, 8 and suffers from significant weaknesses.",
    "9 Drawing on examples from different fields, Veale and Binns show how decisionmaking based on profiling can challenge the applicability of Article 22 GDPR.",
    "10 Similarly, Hänold argues that \"Art.",
    "22 GDPR in reality only achieves a limited protective function\" 11 because its scope of application does not cover situations where profiling supports a decision."
  ]
}